{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hawthorne_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205698243/1937120201/0796.xml":{"full_text":"16\nHotel Employes and Management Slated\nTo Begin Negotiations Soon, After\nWorkers Pile Up Union Vote\nBy THE LABOR NEWS EDITOR\nDevoted to the interests of labor in the District of\nColumbia, this column appears every Thursday. News\nitems intended for publication here should be mailed in\ntime to reach the Labor News Editor by noon of the\npreceding Wednesday.\nNegotiations between the organ-<\nized employes of the Manger Ho\ntels of Washington and the man\nagement of s\nthese enter\nprises are to\nget under way F\nin the imme-\ndiate future. I\nPreliminary F\nand formal g J\u2019\nsteps have al- L\nready been Ha*\ntaken, culmi- H\nnating in the\nelection held 1\nTuesday under 1\nthe auspices 01 K A\nthe National V M\nLabor Rela\ntions Board. Oarland P. Webb\nThis, the first of a series of pro- j\ngressive steps to be taken by the 1\nManger Hotels, which include the\nHamilton, the Annapolis and the\nHay-Adams, and the Hotel and\nRestaurant Employes, showed that\nthe voters from these hostelries\nfavored union representation, 85\nper cent voting.\nThe two locals of the Hotel and\nRestaurant Employees Alliance\nconcerned were Local 781, the\nCooks, Waitresses and Waiters\n(which represents these workers\nat the Annapolis) and Local 80\nwhich represents the maids, bell\nmen, doormen, painters, telephone\noperators, cigar stand clerks, eleva\ntor operators, timekeepers and\nhousemen in all three hotels.\nLocal 781, of which Garland P.\nWebb is business agent, has con- j\ntracts with ten Washington hotels,\nincluding the Hamilton, but Local\n80 has been organized only since\nAugust 3.\nBEARING POSTPONED\nON LABOR CHARGES\nHearing on charges of unfair\nlabor practices, filed against the\nFuller Construction Company of\nRed Bank, N. J.,\nnon-union con\ntractors who\nwer awarded\nthe contract\nfor the new\nChain Bridge,\ns c h e d u 1 ed to\nstart before\nCarl E. Shedler,\n-a solicitor for\nthe Department\nof Labor, last\nI Monday, had to\nI be p o s t p oned\ndue to failure\nto file necessary\ndata on time.\nLeslie L. SI yen\nThe charges were filed by the\nDistrict Commissioners after the\nWashington Building Trades Coun\ncil submitted information reported\nto have been gathered by several\nbusiness agents of local building\ntrades unions.\nIncluded among witnesses ex\npected to appear at the hearing\nto prpr cute the charges, filed un\nder the Bacon-Davis Act which re\nquires payment of \u201cprevailing\u201d\nwage rates on construction proj\nects for the Government, are John\nIfc. WASHINGTON WAS GOOD TO US\n...SO WE\u2019LL BE GOOD TO YOU\nIf OPTICAL SPECIALS FOR OUR BIRTHDAY SALE\nmust please you\nWWTO Save 15% to 33 1-3%\nCr? j Dr. Block, graduate optometrist since 1908, will scientifically examine your\nI? f e yes- Satisfaction absolutely guaranteed.\nB NOW-SAVE ON EYE WEAR\nfl'\u2018 fl I Rimless Glasses Engraved Frames\nML\u2014 m JC--1 QUALITY! STYLE! COM- Stylish frames quality\nFORT I White single- ja built \u2014for long, hard\nvision lenses mounted U QR 4 95\nIn white or pink gold-\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0\u2019*** Individually fitted to\u2014\nKWCSat.- a fllled engraved frame. your face. BIRTHDAY\nJ BIRTHDAY SALE PRICE SALE PRICE\nt Folding Oxfords Rimless Mounting\nJk. Always smart always To bring your present\nappropriate. White gold- m glasses right up to style.\nBUTT'S* 1 I? 1 1 graved and fitted J7 k White or pink gold-filled BR Q E\nx 1 h newest comfort U -rigid bndge. Fitted K\nI no\u00ab\u00ab re sta._U6ually much K, jj with new pearlold\" nose VW\nB^ E BAL K\nSpecial \u201cBirthday Sal?** prices on all cylindrical and Bi-focal Lenses\nand our entire stock of frames.\ny W W\u00ab will open a Charge Account for you.\nPay for your glasses as low a* SOc a week.\nKoh-\n1114 F STREET N.H.\nTelephone RE pubtie 1234\ni Locher, executive secretary; C. F.\nPrcller, president, and Arthur L.\nj Schoenthal, vice president of the\nBuilding Trades Council: J. P.\nJ Shields, business agent for Hoist\ning Engineers No. 67; Leslie L.\nI Myers, business agent for Iron\nworkers No. 5.\nBREWERY WORKERS\nTO HOLD ELECTION\nBrewery and Yeast Workers\nLocal Union No. 48 will elect offi-\nI cers for the coming year at the\nI regular December meeting sched\nuled to be held Thursday evening,\nDecember 9.\nHarry J. Thompson, business\ni agent, was elected for a three\nyear term last year and carries\nover. William H. Ryan, president,\nwas re-nominated, as were William\nM. Porter and L. B. Thompson. H.\nHeiser and Melvin Coulter were\nnominated for vice president.\nHoward F. Cudmore, recording\nsecretary; Charles Lederer, finan\ncial secretary, and Adam Knudson,\ntreasurer, were nominated without\nopposition.\nNominees for trustee, of whom\nthree are to be elected, include C.\nP. Knowles, Richard Schmidt,\nCharles Meier, Leslie Morris, C.\nSchrader, Louis Hoover and John\nKraft. Four were nominated for\nauditors, three to be elected, in\neluding L. M. Green. Moyer Mason,\nC. L. Cox and Frank Rose.\nTELEGRAPH HILL\nTelegraph Hill, famous San Fran\ncisco landmark, is so called be\ncause in early days news of ships\u2019\narrival was flashed from its sum\nmit by heliograph.\nMaine leads the nation\nin POTATO production\u2014\nMaine Potatoes lead\nin flavor and food values\nLook for the blue and red stripes on bags and containers which\nidentify Genuine State of Maine Potatoes, grown, graded\nand shipped under State supervision.\nDial your radio to \u201cThe Girl From Maine\u201d\u2014Marjorie Mills.\nEach Tuesday and Thursday at 1:15 P. M. over Station WOL\nMAINE DEVELOPMENT COMMISSION\nPRODUCTS DIVISION AUGUSTA, {MAINS\nWh hm MMbM\nDECLINE IN AUTO\nSALES TO FORCE\nGM HOURS CUT\nCompany Will Avoid\nLayoffs If Possible\nFLINT, Mich., Dee. 2 (1.N.5.).\nWith the retail market for new\ncars dropping alarmingly in the\npresent business recession, Gen\neral Motors Corporation, through\nVice President C. E. Wilson, today\nannounced it will be forced to cut\nproduction schedules in most of\nits plants.\nThe production cut, Wilson said\nat a meeting here last night, will\nbe effected through a cut in the\nwork week hours to a figure below\nthe standard 40-hour week.\nWilson stressed the fact that\nGeneral Motors plans to hold to\nits agreement with the ClO\u2019s\nUnited Automobile Workers Union\nby cutting hours as low as possible\nbefore resorting to widespread lay\noffs.\n\u201cWe will be unable to main\ntain a 40-hour work week sched\nule for the next few months,\u201d he\nsaid. \u201cThere will also be further\nlayoffs.\u201d\nMany automobile companies al\nready have been forced to cut pro\nduction work to a four-day week,\nincluding some GM plants.\nWilson denied that labor troubles\nin the plants will force the further\nproduction cut, but said \u201clabor\ntroubles during the past year in\nvarious industries and the public\u2019s\nloss of confidence is largely re\nsponsible for the present business\nrecession.\u201d\nHe pointed out that the business\nI recession slashed GM retail sales\nafter the corporation had spent\nmillions to expand facilities to\nmeet the increased demand that\nwas anticipated throughout the in\ndustry for the 1938 model year.\nMost of the other automobile com\npanies, too, invested heavily in ex\npansic projects.\nWilson said present retail sale\nof GM cars is only two-thirds as\nhigh as the sale of cars to the\npublic a year ago.\n\u201cOur dealers on November 20\nhad 85.000 more new cars in\nstock than last year,\u201d he said.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES THURSDAY, DECEMBER 2, 1937\nBootleg Coal\nRule by State\nProposed\nNEW YORK, Dec. 2 (1.N.5.).\nState control of Pennsylvania\u2019s\ngigantic \u201cbootleg\u201d mining opera\ntions was proposed in a report by\nthe Anthracite Coal Industry Com\nmission, now ready for the inspec\ntion of Gov. George H. Earle.\nOn the theory that \u201ccoal sold\nat bootleg prices is what cripples\nthe legitimate operators,\u201d the com\nmission appointed by Governor\nEarle proposes \u201cthat the State\nlease or buy the lands in the three\ncounties where the bootlegging\ngoes on and produce and sell the\ncoal at market prices.\u201d\nMorris L. Ernst, commission\nmember who revealed the sub\nstance of the report, also asserted\nthat \"through cooperative market\ning agencies and the allocation of\nproduction, we believe that $2 a\nton can be saved on the price to\nthe consumer.\u201d\nOperators turned down a pro\nposal to take over the mining of\nthe two to foqr million tons of\ncoal now produced by bootleg\nminers and the commission then\ndecided .to recommend that the\nState take control.\nAnother meeting of the commis\nsion will be held next week either\nin Washington or Philadelphia.\nThe report will be given to Gov\nernor Earle when he returns from\nEurope on December 16.\nUAW Will Retain\nSit-Down Strikes\nPITTSBURGH, Dec. 2 (1.N.5.).\nRichard T. Frankensteen, vice\npresident of the United Automo\nbile Workers, says the union will\nnot abandon the sit-down strike\nas a weapon in industrial disputes.\nHe says:\n\u201cWe\u2019ve never tried to justify\nthe sit-down as legal, but it is\nan act of poetic Justice.\u201d\nThe Coat That Won Her a \u00bb10,000.-\n000-A-Year Husband. Not Mink Nor\nErmine But dust a Coat of Gilt-Radia\ntor Paint That Promoted the Bur\nlesque Dancer to Wife of Europe\u2019s\nRichest Gentleman-Adventurer. An\nIllustrated Feature In The American\nWeekly, with Sunday\u2019s Washington\nHerald-Times.\nllllflH\u00df\u00dfftfll\n'.J I JEx? 4I*. JU- w..\nbB-B fl Bk Wilk\nfl. fl| qfl Olffl w inMiipr\nfor your old radio\n0 1 on b ran d new\nselling regularly al 79.95\nyou pay only P\n1\nwith your old set m\nFor a limited time only! Here at the HecYit Co.\nA your old radio is worth S3O regardless of make\nor condition on the purchase of this brand new\nRCA Victor. A marvel of performances, thanks\nB to these exclusive RCA features:\nZ\u2018 Metal Tubes